text: In 2006, I was 10 years old. Cars became an instant favourite. In 2011 I was 15. Cars 2 was a lot of fun and slightly darker in tone, despite the disappointing third act. I'm now 21 years old. The tone of this teaser is incredible. These movies have been such a big part of my childhood memories, and Pixar knows that there are people like me out there who grew up on and love this franchise and they're making a trilogy, like Toy Story, with an appropriately serious tone to the third instalment to match our age. Thank you, Pixar.

text: Spoiler Alert: It's actually all a dream sequence. "Everything will change" refers to the fact that when McQueen wakes up, he finds that he is actually a human, trapped inside a car. He finds that his whole reality where everyone is a car is actually fake, Matrix style. Then he gets out of the car. He finds a group of other humans who have discovered the same thing, and they proceed to try to liberate the world from their imprisonment inside their cars. But there's also an evil organization trying to stop them.  They had to outdo the action in the last one somehow, so they upped the action, and made it more like the Matrix, while also mixing in some social commentary on how humans are spending large amounts of time inside of vehicles these days.

text: From what I can get from the trailer and description, McQueen is racing in a new generation of race cars that are quicker than him, but it doesn't stop him from competing. I'm assuming that the car (black with blue or violet stripes) speeding in those quick shots pushed McQueen to go to speeds that he couldn't handle, leading him to crash. From there, he'll meet some technician who wants to help fix him and make his body more competitive to win the piston cup. There will be parts where it might go back to doc's (Hudson hornet) race days that 'inspire' McQueen or the times with doc and McQueen that we didn't get to see between cars and cars 2. I'm sure it's gonna go back to radiator springs or at least see some of the other characters. The trailer looks good and I hope the final product meets with the expectations of a good Pixar movie and not flop like some others films that didn't do so well.

text: It was almost two years ago when I read the book by Pixar's creator, Ed Catmull, called Creativity Inc. On the whole, it was a very good book, and I would still advise you all to check it out. Yet, when I was reading it, I noticed something eerie: he never once mentioned Cars 2, at all. It would've obviously not fit in his narrative of success, so understood it, and hoped he intended to just bury it alongside Planes (even though it was technically his decision to produce Planes, as he has been Disney's CEO ever since they merged.) Suffice it to say, that goodwill is gone now.

text: I have a few thoughts on this teaser:  1) The animation here is outstanding.  It looks photorealistic at many points. 2) I was not expecting such a somber teaser for a Pixar film. 3) Already, this film is giving off a vibe of having far more heart and maturity than "Cars 2."  "Cars" was solid Pixar, but "Cars 2" was disappointingly average, though still watchable.  It seems Lasseter and Pixar listened to the critiques of "Cars 2" and tried to make improvements for "Cars 3."

text: Cars 3 Lighting Mcqueen is a car who grows up dreaming of going fast. Mcqueen acts as a replacement driver after Terry decides to take a break while in last place. After starting in last place in place of Cheveaux, McQueen finishes in third place. McQueen becomes the new great in the NASCAR and gains fame and fortune at Dennit Racing. While racing, he kisses his wife, Sally.Mcqueen persuades Dennit Racing to sponsor an additional team car. McQueen arranges to have his best friend, Mater, on his team. While Mcqueen and Mater succeed throughout competitions, their new teammate, French Formula One rival Jackson Storm is tough to beat. He outperforms them to become Piston's latest success story.Desperate to dominate, Mcqueen exceeds his limitations and crashes at Charlotte Motor Speedway, which included his car rolling and flipping in the air.While paramedics attempt to take him to the hospital, Mcqueen runs around on the track. Wearing only his helmet and underwear,¬† insists he is on fire. During his recovery, McQueen believes he is paralyzed. After deliberately stabbing himself in the leg, he realizes that he is not.Now, McQuenn is eager to rejoin the NASCAR circuit. Before a race at Rockingham Speedway, Mcqueen completed a test drive, but fear caused him to drive exceedingly slow. Mcqueen is fired from Dennit Racing and his pit crew now works for storm. Jamie McMurray acts as McQueen's replacement for the Rustiees car. Desperate to remain wealthy, Sally divorces McQueen and marries Mater. After accusing Mater of ruining his life, McQueen ends their friendship.Lightning moves in with his mom, Lucy Mcqueen. McQueen's¬† sons, Walker and Texas Ranger join him as he works as a pizza delivery car. After colliding with a shopping cart, McQueen loses his driver's license and he is reduced to using a bicycle.While McQueen is not well, his father, Reese, teaches him to drive with a live cougar in his car. After his father leaves, McQueen talks to his assistant and partner, Susan, who persuades him to return to NASCAR, since it is in his nature to drive fast. After deciding to take Susan's advice and race at the Talladega 500, Lightning and Susan become love interests. With the Talladega 500 on his mind, McQueen gathers a race car and pit crew.Before the race, McQueen makes amends with Sally, Girard and Mater, while uniting with his pit crew chief and close friend, Doc Hudson. McQueen is forced to start in last place, after spare parts were donated to build the engine in McQueen's new race car. At the start of the race, McQueen passes all of the drivers, except Girard. In the closing laps, Mater uses a slingshot technique for McQueen to pass Girard.The replacement driver of the Rustees car causes a massive wreck that causes all drivers to crash, excluding Mcqueen and Girard. On the final lap of the race, McQueen and Girard collide with each other and their race cars roll towards the finish line. McQueen and Girard exit their cars and run towards the finish line. In the background, "We Belong" by Pat Benatar is playing. McQueen wins the race, but he and Girard are disqualified for exiting their cars, so Mater officially wins the Talladega 500. At the time of the first major crash, Mater was in third place.Being the sore loser he is, McQueen drives off a cliff and diesTHE END!

text: I have a theory. At 0.23 we briefly see Lightning McQueen with flame decals on his car. The NASCAR driver who was known for flame decals on his car was Jeff Gordon, a racer who exploded onto the NASCAR scene (much like McQueen in the original movie) but was seen by many as past his prime and retired in late 2015 after a fruitless but competitive run at a Cup victory. The 2015 racing season would be a logical time for the story of Cars 3 to be conceived, given that animated movies take a year or two (or sometimes three) to produce. Jeff Gordon also made a cameo in Cars 2 as the voice of Jeff Corvette, so we know Pixar and Gordon have worked together in the past. So, my conclusion is that this movie borrows heavily from the career of one of the greatest NASCAR drivers of all time: Jeff Gordon.

text: I've seen a lot of NASCAR style wrecks, and this is Carl Edwards Talladega and Brad Keselowski Atlanta kind of bad. For those that don't know, in both wrecks, both of those driver's cars went airborne and wrecks near the catch fence, much like what McQueen is doing here. If it weren't for current safety protocols and equipment upgrades, both of those drivers would have been severely injured. I suspect something similar for Lighting in Cars 3 - possibly a Rocky-style return arc, much like Kyle Busch's return from an injury to win the NASCAR Sprint Cup in 2015.

text: The full trailer is supposedly coming out later this week, or at least some time within the next couple weeks, so we'll see if this is really going to be "dark."  Now, I'm not thinking it's going to be "dark," but there's definitely (probably) going to be more a more mature tone to this compared to the other two. The colors of the animation in the first two were vibrant, eye-catching enough so: look, kids! fast bright colors! be distracted! The colors here are more... "realistic" (or "muted?" not sure what the term is for that) so they may be trying to make it for all audiences? Or this is a flashback sequence of McQueen looking back to what happened?

Since he is older than Flash,  he retired from racing and now train Rookies. Now that would start like The opening race for a new season Flash getting ready since he is a veteran his getting ready when suddently he hear his name from a know voice which is Chick. Anyway, he go see him and then tease each other. Then at the end, he just point to Flash an electric car and say "It's my rookie, I trained him by myself and he gonna beat you" Then Flash is just whatever it's his first season, nothing to worry about. Then race begin, few laps later Flash realize how munch he underestimate Chick Rookie and decide to push himself to the limit in order to beat him and not be humiliated by Chick. Sadly, he commit an error he already done in the past. He don't change his tires in order to not lose time . His tires explode, he try to slown down but lose control and then crash himself.  He survive the crash but won't be able to run ever again and will have larges troubles to move without assistance (exactly where Mater could be finally usefull and a revelant character). text: Well..... that certainly isn't what I expected. I'm not entirely sure what I expected, but since Cars was decent and lighthearted, but fairly unmemorable, and Cars 2 was also lighthearted but crappy, I certainly wasn't expecting something this ominous and weirdly dark. I'm not particularly excited for this movie, as I've always felt this was Pixar's weakest franchise, and it didn't need a third movie. I'm also not expecting Pixar to take this movie in as dark of a direction as this teaser implies. But I will say I'm intrigued at the very least.

text: If you read the description it's kinda easy to see where this is going. The organisers of the piston cup are wanting to go green with their races (relevant to modern racing times) but their leading star Lightning McQueen doesn't want to change having realised who he really is in the first Cars. So the piston cup organiser's set up a one off race to determine what's the future for the sport, hybrid engines or standard gasoline engines. I think this trailer is about this one off race. the reason is because there are still gasoline engines to be heard and electrical whines from the hybrid cars. I also feel like McQueen would have had a falling out with his old friends from radiator springs as he's obviously not pitted and stuck to his way of "Gass no tyres". This to me seems like he's gone back to his old self before radiator springs because his friends have gone with the "hybrid" way of thinking and that sets McQueen down a path of self destruction that ends in a bad wreck which sees the piston cup become a hybrid only competition. This failure forces McQueen to leave town disgusted and outed by the sport he loves he hits rock bottom until a new friendly technician recognises him and slowly but surely coaxes McQueen to a state of acceptance. With McQueen found his old friends surprise him pleading with him to just try it. So McQueen becomes hybrid and goes on his first drive and realises the power of hybrid and the clean running like nature intended (imagine McQueen and Sally driving scene) So eventually this leads McQueen to try and re enter the Piston Cup to prove he's still got what it takes but the Owners have a new poster boy (he's not a bad guy) and don't want him until he shows off/tells them he's hybrid. He gets put back into the series and having missed out on some races finds himself with his back against the wall in trying to win every races with his old and new friends. The final race, it's all down between the new poster boy and a resurgent McQueen. But disaster strikes as McQueen suffers an electrical fault and has another wreck on the last lap. He's finished he thinks but then he gets a push from behind as the new posterboy is pushing him over the line. McQueen has a flashback and realises he did this once before suddenly realising he's come full circle, he's the legend and the posterboy is the new rookie. With McQueen finishing infront of poster boy he wins the Piston Cup. The end could pretty much write itself. McQueen gives the Rookie words of wisdom, McQueen retires and enjoys a nice relaxing drive with all his friends. The End.  Or that's how I think it will go anyways!!

To get back in the game, he will need the help of an eager young race technician, Cruz Ramirez, with her own plan to win, plus inspiration from the late Fabulous Hudson Hornet and a few unexpected turns. Proving that #95 isn‚Äôt through yet will test the heart of a champion on Piston Cup Racing‚Äôs biggest stage!*  Mcqueen doesn't die. The teaser is just setting the tone for the movie at how it isn't going to be flowers and rainbows, but rather determination and rising back to glory. TL:DR me, I really do not care. text: Here's my theory: The teaser happens in the real world and shows a near fatal crash that leaves a human Nascar racer named McQueen (nicknamed Lightning) comatose. The events of Cars 1 and 2 are a dream. Cars 3 deals with him waking up and saying goodbye to the fictional world he created based on his life. The conflict is that he spent years in this fictional world and perhaps doesn't want to leave.

text: You know if you look on the side at 15 seconds and slow the video speed down to 0.5 and pause at the right time, you'll see the words, LOS ANGELES NATIONAL SPEEDWAY (make sure you look at the banners that they have on the walls, because that's where it is). If it's international that explains that black super car you see in the middle of the trailer. Not all of the cars are American. Oh yeah and this is very interesting but you know how this is the LOS ANGELES NATIONAL SPEEDWAY? This is the exact same place where Lightning had the race at the end of the first movie. Where he saved Strip (the old blue car). You have to say it really looks different. I originally had a theory where the race took place in Radiator Springs, but I was wrong. I hope they come out with another movie after this one!

text: For some reason, this trailer's mere existence is absolutely hilarious to me. First movie and probably the second featured horrid writing and just sub-mediocrity in every area, clearly driven by the "this is for kids! and kids are stupid! let's market!" mentality. Kachow! But then... I'm laughing just typing this, because--*what?* there are just so many things you have to wonder, like: is this trailer just a dark and edgy looking thing to catch interest, but the actual movie far from it, or will the movie legitimately feature this lighting, colouring, and overall moodier cinematography and story? How would they even manage that with these cartoon cars? And who came up with this idea, anyway? Did they just burst into the office like, "Sandra, you won't believe how brilliant this idea I've just come up with is right now! You know our movies about little cartoon cars with a target audience ranging from three to eight years old?" I don't even know in the slightest what to expect from this movie, it's just--it's just so funny I'm sorry.

text: McQueen struggles to compete against this new set of modern rookie racers, with new and improved aerodynamical efficiency. 00:23 it looks like McQueen trying to drift on asphalt, these are new tricks which he isn't built to do. Lightning's main racing rival (#20) is dominating the speedway - as well as other fresh race cars. Cruz Ramirez is stated to be a young technician, out to help the 'champion' Lightning McQueen. After the terrifying crash his vehicle will need to be renewed to perform again, I am guessing, Cruz installs new parts onto Lightning in order for him to be able to compete (have a chance of winning); keep his racing legacy. Ramirez's dreams of being a technician succeeds as the all-star takes what is his own, the Piston Cup! However, there are several other sources which highlight their own respected perspectives, or elaborate on specific aspects. The movie will focus on the emotional end of each character, especially McQueen. It seems like the 'Lightning' in his name is an alias given by the fans to resemble his speed, sadly, it no longer works and I wouldn't be surprised if it has been made a mockery of... His friends and family more importantly we will be seeing more of than the actual comedy, racing action etc. Most of the events will relate back to the 'legendary' Hudson hornet as they share similar stories, the King has more than likely retired. This is a story-driven movie instead of the comedic tone in the first installment, or spy-action as in the second franchise, this one picks up a darker tone that, gradually lightens throughout till the end. //NOTE: It doesn't seem like the skid, or even a tyre puncture, can cause his vehicle to flip over! Scene(s) has definitely occured on separate timescales not one after another. Thank You for your time reading my opinion-based comment. I would not mind argumentative replies. Please try to maintain a mature manner in the speech. Have a nice day! ~Ka-Chow!

It's as if it's a racing movie with a car that looks like McQueen, that just borrows the title "Cars".

text: Guys, I remember how over-the-top silly Cars 2 was.  This, to me, would actually be a nice change of pace.  And personally, sometimes, the Animation world needs to get serious sometimes, let the kids know that the real world is not all glittery and filled with butterflies!  I mean, y'all remember how serious Toy Story 3 got towards the end, before the Claw changed the tone?  And still, PIXAR knew exactly what it was doing...we have tom remember that.  So honestly, I'm really looking forward to seeing this; this'll be the first Pixar movie I will have seen since Monsters U.

text: I do see a lot of people commenting about how this is similar to Doc Hudson's accident mentioned in Cars 1 because he crashed in a race of his.  I do agree with this, but that makes me think that us, as the audience, might finally be able to see what actually happened to Doc Hudson instead of McQueen and Hudson talking about it with a newspaper article of the accident behind them.   There is also another thing that I would like to bring up as well: During McQueen's shot before the accident, we don't really see what happens to him causing him to crash into the wall followed by him flipping over his side with debris flying everywhere. There are two things that come to my mind during that moment:  1. At the beginning of McQueen's scene, we see him use his breaks, veer left, then veer right into the wall on his right. Now, I'm not one to know about car racing so I probably shouldn't say this, but I don't think it's possible to crash into a wall like that then go into a full side flip. I feel like he crashed into the wall, slowly rolled backwards/forwards, and got hit by the other racers, causing him to flip over.  2. Not only is it similar to the Hudson crash, but the King from Cars 1 sort-of went out like this as well when Chick Hicks bumped into him causing him to flip out into the grass. Just something I thought that I would mention.

text: I hate it when people say that Cars was one of Pixar's least successful movies and that it was only for marketing toys. They had so much merchandise BECAUSE the film was successful!! Frozen did a ton of marketing, but you don't see people judging that movie as just a movie for merchandise! Now PLANES was just for marketing!! And The Good Dinosaur is hands down Pixar's weakest movie! Cars though, was an absolute masterpiece with the best plot, jokes, and characters. People just didn't appreciate it as much because not everyone is a Nascar fan! The people who are Nascar fans saw more references and jokes than the people who aren't. The people who are middle aged appreciated the movie more than the younger generation because they were able to understand the references. We went to see it 3 times when it came into theaters and it's still my mom's favorite movie to this day! Just because you couldn't understand it, doesn't mean the movie was bad!!   Also, I don't see why people hated Cars 2 either. That had a whole different feel from the first movie, but did it in an awesome way! The whole spy car mystery plot was so interesting to watch! They put more of Mater in the second movie because people loved him in the first! It wasn't as good as the first of course, but there was nothing wrong with it! People need to leave their hate on a movie that actually deserves it. Not an amazing movie like Cars.

text: In all honesty, I think the original plot for C3 would've worked better. But this is still good...if Lightning retired. I mean, as shown in this teaser, he was shaking to keep up with the NGs. Yeah, training helps, but it still won't work. Changing your engine/upgrade to a modern casting (like in Race-O-Rama) can work, if done right. Which means Lightning could've kept his model from C2.  I'm not bashing this film at all. This film was pretty amazing. I actually love the Cars franchise out of every Pixar (Disney in general) production.
